@node "About" "ConfigTHOR.guide/About"
@next "Systems Configuration"
@prev "Main"
@toc "Main"

About
*****

ConfigTHOR  is  the  configuration program for THOR.  It offers a wide
range of options to customize THOR for your needs.


@endnode

@node "Systems Configuration" "ConfigTHOR.guide/Systems Configuration"
@next "User Info"
@prev "About"
@toc "Main"

Systems Configuration
*********************

This is the window used to configure new systems.  You will have to
enter some information:

The  @{i}name  @{ui}of the system (BBS or Internet provider) you want to add.

The  @{i}packet name @{ui}the system uses.  Remember to omit extensions.  Note
that  a  packet  name  is  not mandatory and is only required on system
types where you actually receive you mail in packet/file.  TCP systems
for  Internet usage do not required a packet name, but if you choose
to provide on, Thor will assume this is a mailbox and parse it as  one.
 This can be handy for SMTPd where you receive your mail via SMTP
instead  of  POP3.   Please refer to the THOR.faq for how to set this
up.


       Some examples:
     
        System Type:   Example grab:    Packet name:
        ------------   -------------    ------------
        ABBS/MBBS      thule.lzx        thule
        QWK            thule1256.qwk    thule
        SOUP           soup3683.soup    soup
        Omen           omenb1.zip       omenb1
        BlueWave       romeo.zip        romeo
        Hippo          girls.lzh        girls
        Fido           1CA9B792.SU0     #?.((MO|TU|WE|TH|FR|SA|SU)[0-9]|PKT)
        UUCP           john             john
     
       Use the maximum number of letters possible to identify  the
       grabs,  e.g.,  "WHT" if grabs are named "WHT010993.QWK" and the
       numbers change from session to session.
       Do not use the same packet name on two systems!

The  @{i}type @{ui}of  system  or  message format on the system you are calling
(choose from the list).

A few other configuration windows are used for other parameters on a
system wide level:


 @{" User Info           " link "User Info"}  - User information relevant to this system
 @{" Files-Paths         " link "Files-Paths"}  - Files and paths relevant to this system
 @{" Import-Export       " link "Import-Export"}  - Import/Export options relevant to this system
 @{" Type Options        " link "Type Options"}  - Special configuration only relevant to this system type

See @{"Installation.guide (Setting up a system)" link "Installation.guide/Setting up a system"}.


@endnode

@node "User Info" "ConfigTHOR.guide/User Info"
@next "Files-Paths"
@prev "Systems Configuration"
@toc "Systems Configuration"

User information
****************

In this window, information about yourself can be entered.  Not all of
these  options  are  used  by  all  system  types,  and  some  of this
information  is  collected  from  your keyfile (if you have registered
THOR, which we hope you have).

@{b}Systems and Conference Configuration:@{ub}

    @{b}EMail Address@{ub}
          This  is  the  electronic  address you have on this
          system/conference.  The  EMail address is mostly used on
          Fido-systems and Internet-systems (SOUP  and  UUCP).   So,
          if  you  use  an  Internet system type (TCP, TCP_ONLINE,
          SOUP or UUCP), enter you email address here, if you use a
          Fido system type, enter you netmail address here.

@{b}Only Systems Configuration:@{ub}

    @{b}User Name@{ub}
          This  is your real name.  This name will be used as default
          on systems supported  with a NComm script, and as your real
          name on Internet type of systems (like TCP, SOUP and UUCP).

    @{b}Street Address@{ub}
          This is your street address.

    @{b}Address@{ub}
          This is your city and zip code.

    @{b}Country@{ub}
          This is the country you live in.

    @{b}Phone@{ub}
          This is your phone number.


@endnode

@node "Files-Paths" "ConfigTHOR.guide/Files-Paths"
@next "Import-Export"
@prev "User Info"
@toc "Systems Configuration"

Files and paths
***************

@{b}Tag file@{ub}
     This  is  the  tag  file.  The file must have one tag on each
     line.  A random  tag  from  this  file  will  be a added under the
     signature in messages  you  write.   If you want to use multiline
     tags, this can be done  by  using  backslash  n  (\n) to separate
     lines in the tag.  The field can be left empty, in which case no
     tag will be used.

     A cycle gadget will let you choose to use the global defined tag
     file, don't use a tag file on this system/conference or use the
     tag file you define here.

@{b}Systems and Conference Configuration:@{ub}

    @{b}Signature@{ub}
          This  is the signature that is appended at the end of the
          message file before it is imported into the editor (and in
          front of any taglines).

          There are 3 ways of adding signatures:

         @{b}String@{ub}
               The contents of the signature string gadget will contain
               the string to be imported into the message.

         @{b}File@{ub}
               The  contents  of the signature string gadget is a file
               name of a text file that will be imported into the
               message.

         @{b}Command@{ub}
               The  contents  of the signature string gadgets is a
               shell command that will  receive  arguments with the
               template "BBSNAME/K,CONFNAME/K" when run and must write
               the output to stdout.

          A  cycle  gadget  lets you choose to use the global defined
          signature, don't  use  a signature on this system/conference
          or use the signature you define here.

    @{b}Entering Confs@{ub}
          If  this  window is opened from the Systems Configuration,
          this is the Arexx  script  that  will  be run whenever you
          enter any conference on this  system.   When  in  Conference
          Configuration, this is the Arexx script that will be run
          whenever you enter this conference.

          (See @{"ARexx scripts" link "ARexx scripts"} for further information).

    @{b}Leaving Confs@{ub}
          If  this  window is opened from the Systems Configuration,
          this is the Arexx  script that will be run whenever you leave
          a conference on this system.   When  in  Conference
          Configuration, this is the Arexx script that will be run
          whenever you leave this conference.

          (See @{"ARexx scripts" link "ARexx scripts"} for further information).

@{b}Only Systems Configuration:@{ub}

    @{b}Download Dir@{ub}
          This  is  the  download  directory  where  grabs  and packets
          that you download  from  systems  will  be  searched  for.
          This  setting will override  the  globally  defined  download
          directory.   This  is  not required for TCP systems, but if
          you provide one, it should usually be UUMAIL:  provided you
          get you mail by some other means than POP3.

    @{b}Upload Dir@{ub}
          This is the upload directory where reply packets will be
          placed.  This setting will override the globally defined
          upload directory.

    @{b}Entering System@{ub}
          This Arexx script will be run whenever you enter this system
          in THOR.

          (See @{"ARexx scripts" link "ARexx scripts"} for further information).

    @{b}Leaving System@{ub}
          This Arexx script will be run whenever you leave this system
          in THOR.

          (See @{"ARexx scripts" link "ARexx scripts"} for further information).


@endnode

@node "Import-Export" "ConfigTHOR.guide/Import-Export"
@next "Type Options"
@prev "Files-Paths"
@toc "Systems Configuration"

Import and Export options
*************************

@{b}Only Systems Configuration:@{ub}

    @{b}Event Arc@{ub}
          This  defines  the  archiver  type  to  use  when  archiving
          the reply package.   The default is the archiver defined in
          the system type, and you normally don't have to change it.

    @{b}Script Flags@{ub}
          If  a  system  type  is  supported with a script, all or some
          of these flags will be available.

         @{b}Get Newfiles@{ub}
               Request a list of new files from the remote system.

         @{b}Auto DL Private@{ub}
               Automatically download files uploaded private to you.

         @{b}Auto Log Off@{ub}
               Automatically log off after the script session has ended.

         @{b}Get Bulletins@{ub}
               Automatically collect updated bulletins since you last
               logon.

         @{b}Ansi Menus@{ub}
               Configure the remote system to use ANSI menus.

         @{b}Use Colors@{ub}
               Configure the remote system to display colors while you
               are online.

    @{b}Add users@{ub}
          If  this  gadget  is  checked, all users that receive or send
          messages will  be  added  to  the user database.  If this
          gadget is @{i}NOT @{ui} checked,  only  users  in mail conferences
          will be added.  On Internet type  of  systems, this option
          will only add users in email when it is selected, and on
          these systems the sortmail setting will override this setting
          on a folder to folder basis.

          You  should  not  use this option on systems with a lot of
          users, e.g.  Internet  news  and  Fidonet.   Parsing  will
          be  slower  if the user database is large.

    @{b}7-bit Mail@{ub}
          This  option  applies  on  system  types where email is sent
          using the Internet.   Selecting  this option will make sure
          all email is sent as 7-bit,  in  compliance  with  RFC  822.
          If  the  mail contains 8-bit characters,  the  mail  will
          be  encoded  using MIME quoted-printable encoding.

@{b}Systems and Conference Configuration:@{ub}

    @{b}Charset@{ub}
          All  messages  in  the  message database is kept in ISO
          character set.  The  messages  in  converted  from  the
          default  charset  to ISO when imported.   By  setting  this
          option to something else than "Default", you  can  select
          what  charset  the messages is to be converted from.
          Usually, the default setting will be correct.

    @{b}Xpk Method@{ub}
          This  is  the Xpk method that will be used when packing
          messages, e.g.  "NUKE"  or  "RAKE".   The  cycle gadget to
          the right can be set to use this  setting,  don't  use Xpk on
          this system/conference or to use the global settings
          (default).

    @{b}Show Own Msgs@{ub}
          If  this  option  is  checked,  messages  written  by  you
          are marked as unread when imported into the database.

    @{b}Line Length@{ub}
          By  setting the contents of this integer gadget to something
          else than 0,  you  can  define  a  custom  line  length  to
          use when replying to messages.   The  default  setting  is
          0, in which case the the system default will be used.

    @{b}Reflow Text@{ub}
          By  checking this option, reformatting text when replying to
          a message is  on  as  default.   Even  if this option is on,
          reflow can still be turned off when replying to a message.

    @{b}Quoting@{ub}
          This  cycle  gadget  defines what type of quoting to apply to
          messages you reply to.  Six different types are supported:

         @{b}Use Global@{ub}
               This will use the quote type defined in the system type
               (or the system quoting if started from the Conference
               Configuration).

         @{b}Default@{ub}
               This  will  put  a  ">" in front of all quoted lines.

         @{b}None@{ub}
               No quoting will be applied to the message.

         @{b}Def+Space@{ub}
               Will put a ">" in front of all lines and puts an extra
               space after the ">"  on  lines  which has not been
               quoted before.  Readability will be higher and it looks
               better.

         @{b}Custom@{ub}
               Lets  you  enter  your  own  character(s) to put before
               lines which are quoted in the string gadget to the right.

         @{b}Initials@{ub}
               Messages will be quoted with the initials of the person
               that wrote the message  replied  to.   If  "Petter
               Nilsen"  wrote a message your are replying to, "PN|"
               will be put in front of all quoted lines.  This is
               commonly used on BBSes and should not be used on the
               Internet.

    @{b}Reply String@{ub}
          This  string will be added at the top of the message when you
          reply.  It may contain several codes that is replaced with
          various information:

                 %S        -   Subject
                 %A        -   Sender address
                 %N        -   Sender full name
                 %F        -   Sender first name
                 %L        -   Sender last name
                 %R        -   Reciever address
                 %E        -   Receiver name
                 %C        -   Conference
                 %I        -   MsgID
                 %O        -   Original messagenr on remote system
                 %D        -   Date

@{i}          NOTE: @{ui}Not all fields are available on all systems. If a field
          is not available, it will be left empty.

          A cycle gadget here may be used to tell THOR when to add a
          reply string:

         @{b}Use Global@{ub}
               The  globally  defined  setting  for reply string will
               be used on this system/conference (default).

         @{b}Only if moved@{ub}
               The reply string will only be used if the message in not
               replyed to in the same conference or to the same user.

         @{b}Always@{ub}
               The reply string will always be used when making a reply.

         @{b}Don't use@{ub}
               Don't use any reply string on this system at all.


@endnode

@node "Type Options" "ConfigTHOR.guide/Type Options"
@next "Global Configuration"
@prev "Import-Export"
@toc "Systems Configuration"

Type specific options
*********************

If  this  gadget  is  not ghosted, selecting it will start an external
configuration program for the system type of the selected system.


@endnode

@node "Global Configuration" "ConfigTHOR.guide/Global Configuration"
@next "Database Options"
@prev "Type Options"
@toc "Main"

Global Configuration
********************


 @{" Database Options " link "Database Options"}  -  Options concering the message database
 @{" Message Options " link "Message Options"}  -  Options concering how the message will look
 @{" Global Paths    " link "Global Paths"}  -  Paths to download and upload directory etc.
 @{" Archivers       " link "Archivers"}  -  Archivers to be used.
 @{" Screen Options  " link "Screen Options"}  -  Screenmode, palette, fonts etc.
 @{" ARexx scripts   " link "ARexx scripts"}  -  Startup/leave ARexx scripts

@{b}Use (config)@{ub}
     Lets you test the global configuration selected.

@{b}Save (config)@{ub}
     Saves the global configuration to disk.

@{b}Last Saved@{ub}
     Loads  the last saved global configuration from disk.  It will be
     used when you select @{i}Use (config)@{ui}.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Cancels all changes made to the global configuration.


@endnode

@node "Database Options" "ConfigTHOR.guide/Database Options"
@next "Message Options"
@prev "Global Configuration"
@toc "Global Configuration"

Global database options
***********************

This  window  is used for setting of parameters related to the message
database.

@{b}Buffers@{ub}
     This  value  defines  the number of buffers the buffering system
     uses.  Note  that 13 is the default number of buffers and you will
     not notice any  significant  speed difference by increasing this
     number, although reading and parsing messages in reference mode is
     slightly faster with a  higher  setting.   The  Buffer  size  has
     much greater influence on performance.

@{b}Buffer Size@{ub}
     This  value  is  the size of each buffer.  Default is 5096, and
     should not  be  any  less (since this is the size of one of the
     hash-tables.)  However, if you have the memory to spare, you
     should increase this for higher  performance.   These  buffers
     are used by BBSRead.library and will be freed when bbsread.library
     is flushed out of memory or after a 5 minutes timeout if the
     library is not in use anymore..  Defining too large  buffer  here
     might  make  THOR  slower  because  of  overhead.  Usually, 20000
     is a good size of the buffer.

@{b}Msgs to Keep@{ub}
     This  value is used when packing conferences.  If the number is
     set to e.g.  100, all messages except for the newest 100 will be
     deleted when you pack messages

     This  is the default for all conferences if nothing else is
     defined in the @{"Conference Configuration" link "Conference Configuration"}.  If you set the checkbox
     gadget to "Ignore", no messages will be packed with this parameter.

     See @{"THOR.guide (Pack-Purge Window)" link "THOR.guide/Pack-Purge Window"}.

@{b}Days to Keep@{ub}
     This  value  is used when packing conferences, unless another
     value is defined  in  the  @{"Conference Configuration" link "Conference Configuration"}.   When
     packing, all messages  older  than this number of days will be
     removed.  This works seemless  together with the @{i}Msgs to Keep
     @{ui}value.  If you set the checkbox  gadget  to  "Ignore",  no
     messages will be packed with this parameter.

     See @{"THOR.guide (Pack-Purge Window)" link "THOR.guide/Pack-Purge Window"}.

@{b}Xpk Method@{ub}
     This  is  the Xpk method that will be used when packing messages,
     e.g.  "NUKE"  or  "RAKE".

@{b}Auto Xpk Packing@{ub}
     If  this  gadget  is  checked,  Xpk packing will be preformed when
     the messages  are  imported  into  the  database.  Otherwise, if
     will only happen when packing messages.

@{b}Haze Levels@{ub}
     This feature is named after Dave 'hazy' Haynie.

     On  emphasize/kills,  any  matching  message  can  be  given a
     special @{i}Haze Level @{ui}.  The various haze-levels are defined in the
     Global Configuration in ConfigTHOR and defines the minimum number
     of days the message is to remain in the messages database before
     it can be purged.

     Tip:   If  you  want  to  keep  your  own messages (the ones you
     write yourself) in the database somewhat longer, setup a @{i}Mark
     Unread @{ui} trigger  on your own email address, then set a haze level
     that'll keep the message in the database longer than other
     messages.


@endnode

@node "Message Options" "ConfigTHOR.guide/Message Options"
@next "Global Paths"
@prev "Database Options"
@toc "Global Configuration"

Global message options
**********************

@{b}Editor@{ub}
     This  cycle  gadget may be either set to "Internal", in which case
     the internal  editor is used, or "External" which will activate
     the string gadget  where you can type in the name and command line
     options to the external  editor  of  your  choice.   Note that if
     you use an external editor  that can open on a public screen,  in
     is suggested that you use THOR's public screen.  It has the name
     "Thor.n", where n is 1 if you are running one copy of THOR.

     The following codes can be used on the command line for the
     external editor definition and will be replaced with the
     appropriate data by THOR:

     %P - pubscreen name

     Note that this code will be at the end of the line passed to the
     editor.

@{b}Tab Size@{ub}
     This  is  the  TAB size used in the internal editor and in the
     message window.

@{b}Auto Next Msg@{ub}
     This  flag  can  be set if you want to go directly to the next
     message when you have replied to the current one.

@{b}No "Next Conf?" Requester@{ub}
     This flag can be set if you don't want a window to pop up when you
     are finished  reading  the  messages  in  a conference.  THOR will
     instead automatically proceed to the next conference.

@{b}Auto Show First Message@{ub}
     If  this  option  is  selected, THOR will automatically show the
     first message  of  a conference when you enter it.  If this is not
     selected, you will have to proceed to the "next" message to get
     THOR to show you the first in a conference.

@{b}Delayed Msg Unmark@{ub}
     When  this option is selected, THOR will not mark the message you
     read as read until you proceed to the next message.

@{b}PGP Command@{ub}
     This is the full path and name of the PGP command you want to use
     when encrypting  messages.   If  nothing is entered here, THOR
     will use the path defined in the env-variable PGPPATH (if
     available).  Please refer to the PGP documentation for further
     information.

@{b}PGP SignID@{ub}
     This  is  the  signature ID you want to use when PGP signing
     messages.  "*" is the default and will use the first item in your
     secret key ring (which  usually only contain one secret key:
     yours).  Please refer to the PGP documentation for further
     information.

@{b}Reply String@{ub}
     This  string  will  be added on top of messages when you reply.  I
     may contain several codes that THOR will replace with various
     information:

       %S        -   Subject
       %A        -   Sender address
       %N        -   Sender name
       %F        -   Sender first name
       %L        -   Sender last name
       %R        -   Reciever address
       %E        -   Receiver name
       %C        -   Conference
       %I        -   MsgID
       %O        -   Original messagenr on remote system
       %D        -   Date

@{i}     NOTE: @{ui}Not all fields are available on all systems. If a field is
     not available, it will be left empty.

     A  cycle gadget is available that can be used to tell THOR when to
     add a reply string:

    @{b}Don't use@{ub}
          Don't use any reply string on this system at all.

    @{b}Only if moved@{ub}
          The reply string will only be used if the message is not
          replied to in the same conference or to the same user.

    @{b}Always@{ub}
          The reply string will always be used when making a reply.

@{b}Tag file@{ub}
     This is the tag file.  A tag is a random joke or a cookie added at
     the end  of  messages you write.  The file must have one tag on
     each line.  If you want to use multiline tags, this can be done by
     using backslash n  (\n) to separate lines in the tag.  The field
     can be left empty, in which case no tag will be used.

     A cycle gadget lets you choose not to use a tag file at all or use
     the tag file you define here.

@{b}Signature@{ub}
     This  is  the  global  signature  that  is  appended at the end of
     the message  file  before  it is imported into the editor (and in
     front of any  taglines).   In a multi-line signature each line can
     be separated with a "\n" (backslash n).

     See @{"THOR.guide (Signature system)" link "THOR.guide/Signature system"}.

     There are 3 methods available to add a signature:

    @{b}String@{ub}
          The contents of the signature string gadget will contain the
          string to be imported into the message.

    @{b}File@{ub}
          The  contents  of the signature string gadget is a file name
          of a text file that will be imported into the message.

    @{b}Command@{ub}
          The  contents  of the signature string gadgets is a shell
          command that will  receive  arguments with the template
          "BBSNAME/K,CONFNAME/K" when run and must write the output to
          stdout.

     A  cycle  gadget lets you choose to don't use a signature on at
     all or use the signature you define here.


@endnode

@node "Global Paths" "ConfigTHOR.guide/Global Paths"
@next "Archivers"
@prev "Message Options"
@toc "Global Configuration"

Global path options
*******************

This  window  is  for  different  paths  which  THOR  will  use in its
operation.  The following paths can be defined here:

@{b}Save dir@{ub}
     With  this  option you can select a directory to be used as
     default in the file requester when you choose Save from the menu.

@{b}Download dir@{ub}
     This  is the download directory where grabs, packets or mailboxes
     that you  download from systems are searched for.  Should be
     configured the same as in your communication program.  If you
     collect mail using UUCP or SMTPd, this should normally be set to
     UUMAIL:

@{b}Upload dir@{ub}
     This is the upload directory where reply packets will be placed.

@{b}ARexx dir@{ub}
     This  is the ARexx directory where THOR defaults to look for new
     ARexx scripts  when adding macros.  This directory is only a
     default for the file  requester,  you  can use arexx scripts from
     other directories as well.

@{b}Temp dir@{ub}
     If  configured,  this directory will be used as temporary storage
     when packing/purging the message database.

@{b}DOS Output File@{ub}
     This  is a CON:  definitions that will be used for parsers and
     packers that  outputs to stdout (command line).  Normally, this
     should be left alone.  The default setting is:

          "CON:0/11/640/200/THOR<->DOS Output/AUTO/SCREEN %s".


@endnode

@node "Archivers" "ConfigTHOR.guide/Archivers"
@next "Screen Options"
@prev "Global Paths"
@toc "Global Configuration"

Global archivers
****************

This  window  is  for editing and adding of archivers.  An archiver is
used  to  uncompress  grabs  or  message  packets  downloaded,  and to
compress  replies  to  be  uploaded.  Several archivers are predefined
and,  in  most  cases,  you  don't need to make any changes.  However,
these functions are available:

@{b}Arc Types@{ub}
     This  is  a list of available archiver types from which you may
     select one  to  edit or delete.  Note that these names are only
     names, and do not actually have to be the @{i}command @{ui}used.

@{b}Edit@{ub}
     Editing of the selected archiver's parameters:

     "Archive  Pattern"  is  the pattern used to identify files packed
     with this  type.  This pattern can be either the file name (e.g.
     "#?.lha") or  the  first  bytes of the file, something like
     "$????2d6c68".  This pattern is compared with the file in
     question, to check if they match.  The"$" is used to define that
     this is a hex-pattern and the "?" is for each  byte that is
     overlooked and not used.  (In the example, the last "2d6c68"  is
     the actual hex-pattern that defines @{i}this @{ui} file to be a file
     archived with LhA.)

     "UnArchive  Command"  is  the  actual  command  used  to  unpack
     these archives.

     "Archive  Command"  is the actual command used to pack message
     packets that  are  to  be  uploaded  to  a system.  Which packer
     to be used is defined in the @{"Systems Configuration" link "Systems Configuration"}.

@{b}New@{ub}
     Adding  of  new archiver types to the list.  You have to edit this
     new type afterwards by entering pattern, unarchive command, etc.

@{b}Delete@{ub}
     Delete the selected archiver type.


@endnode

@node "Screen Options" "ConfigTHOR.guide/Screen Options"
@next "ARexx scripts"
@prev "Archivers"
@toc "Global Configuration"

Global screen options
*********************

@{b}Msg Font@{ub}
     This  option  brings  up a Font Requester.  Only fixed-width fonts
     are shown  here,  and maximum size is set to 20 points.  This font
     is used in  the  listview  for  message text.  Using one of the
     fonts included with THOR is recommended, but any fixed-width font
     can be used.

@{b}List Font@{ub}
     Lets  you  choose  which font to use in all other listviews except
     the message text.

@{b}FSE Font@{ub}
     Lets  you choose the font used in the internal editor.  Note:  If
     this font is too big to fit into the window for the FSE, it will
     default to topaz/8.

@{b}Gadget Font@{ub}
     Lets  you  choose which font to used in all the button gadgets.
     If no font is selected, it will default to the Workbench screen
     font.

@{b}Screen Mode@{ub}
     Lets  you  choose Screen Mode, resolution and number of colors.
     Note: Selecting  8  colors  means  the GUI in THOR will look
     better.  If you want ANSI or MIME attachments to look really good,
     16 colors or higher is  recommended.   (Of course this is a
     tradeoff between speed/chipmem usage  and  ultracoolness).  Please
     consider the number of colors used in any background pictures when
     selecting the number of colors for the screen here.

@{b}Palette@{ub}
     Lets you modify the palette, in 24 bits if supported by your
     hardware.  Only the pens that THOR uses can be edited under OS 3.0.

@{b}Hide main window button panel@{ub}
     Use this option if you don't want to have the bottom gadget row in
     the Main  Window.   The  shortcuts  for these gadgets will still
     work, but more space is used for message text.


@endnode

@node "ARexx scripts" "ConfigTHOR.guide/ARexx scripts"
@next "Conference Configuration"
@prev "Screen Options"
@toc "Global Configuration"

Global ARexx scripts
********************

@{b}THOR Startup@{ub}
     This  is  the  ARexx script THOR will run @{i}async @{ui}just before the
     Startup Window is opened and when THOR is uniconified.

@{b}THOR Quit@{ub}
     This  is  the  ARexx  script THOR will run @{i}sync @{ui}just before any
     windows are closed when you quit THOR and when THOR is iconified.

@{b}Entering Systems@{ub}
     This  is  the  ARexx  script THOR will run @{i}sync @{ui}when entering a
     system  just  before  the  Main window is opened, after parsing of
     any mail packets.

@{b}Leaving Systems@{ub}
     This  is  the  ARexx  script  THOR will run @{i}sync @{ui}when leaving a
     system,  just  before any windows are closed (and after any
     conference leaving script has been run).

@{b}Entering Confs@{ub}
     This  is  the  ARexx  script THOR will run @{i}sync @{ui}when entering a
     conference,  just  after  the first message in the conference has
     been shown.   NOTE:   This  script  will  not  be  run when using
     the ARexx commando SHOWCONFERENCE to avoid any loop situation.

@{b}Leaving Confs@{ub}
     This  is  the  ARexx  script THOR will run @{i}sync @{ui}when leaving a
     conference.

When  the  THOR  Startup  ARexx script is run @{i}async @{ui}, THOR will proceed
as usual and process ARexx commands at the same time.

When  the  other  ARexx  scripts  are run @{i}sync @{ui}, THOR will only prosess
incoming ARexx commands and messages, and nothing else will be done.
THOR  will  not  proceed  until  all outstanding ARexx scripts have
been completed.


@endnode

@node "Conference Configuration" "ConfigTHOR.guide/Conference Configuration"
@next "Index"
@prev "ARexx scripts"
@toc "Main"

Conference Configuration
************************

This gadget lets you configure selected conferences in several ways.

@{b}Delete@{ub}
     Deletes   the   conference   selected  in  the  list  of
     conferences.  @{i}Note:   @{ui}Selecting  this  option  will  delete  ALL
     messages and settings for this conference.

@{b}Sort@{ub}
     This  option  sorts  the conferences alphabetically.  Please note
     that the changes will not be saved to disk until you select "Save".

@{b}Rename@{ub}
     Renames the currently selected conference.

@{b}Top/Up/Down/Bottom@{ub}
     These buttons lets you rearrange the order of the conferences.
     Please note  that  the  changes  will  not be saved to disk before
     you select "Save".

@{b}Days to Keep (conf)@{ub}
     All  conferences  will  use the global option as default.
     However, if you  want  to  enter a specific value for the chosen
     conferences, this will  let  you  enter the number of days to keep
     messages.  The option "Use This" must be selected in the cycle
     gadget for this value to have any effect.

     See @{"THOR.guide (Pack-Purge Window)" link "THOR.guide/Pack-Purge Window"}.

@{b}Msgs to Keep (conf)@{ub}
     Lets  you enter the maximum number of messages allowed in the
     selected conference.   The  option  "Use  This" must be selected
     from the cycle gadget for this value to have any effect.

     See @{"THOR.guide (Pack-Purge Window)" link "THOR.guide/Pack-Purge Window"}.

@{b}Save (conf)@{ub}
     Saves  changes made to all conferences.  After rearranging
     conferences in  the  list,  you  must  use  this option to save
     the new conference order.

@{b}Cancel (conf)@{ub}
     Cancels all changes made to the conferences.

Please see @{"User Info" link "User Info"}, @{"Files-Paths" link "Files-Paths"} and @{"Import-Export" link "Import-Export"} for the other
options in this window.


@endnode

